  "prompt": "Is variance another word for standard deviation?",
  "response": "No, **variance** is not another word for **standard deviation**, although they are closely related concepts in statistics.\n\n- **Variance** measures how spread out a set of numbers is. It is calculated as the average of the squared differences from the mean. Variance is expressed in squared units of the original data.\n\n- **Standard Deviation** is the square root of the variance. It measures the average distance of each data point from the mean and is expressed in the same units as the original data.\n\nIn summary:\n- **Variance** = \u03c3\u00b2 (or s\u00b2 for a sample)\n- **Standard Deviation** = \u221a\u03c3\u00b2 (or \u221as\u00b2 for a sample)\n\nWhile they are mathematically related, they are distinct measures of spread.",
